    <scopecontent id="aspace_f18d25b7337ebfe4b47a46516ad46632">
      <head>Scope and Content</head>
      <p>The David W. Sharpe Collection consists of letter written by Sharpe to his brother, William
        Sharpe, his mother and his sisters from October 10, 1860 to May 10, 1865. The collection
        also includes a cabinet card of Private David W. Sharpe and an 1862 CSA almanac found at
        Yorktown. Topics in the letters include the Siege of Yorktown, the Seven Days Battle
        Campaign, and the Battle of Malvern Hill.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement id="aspace_038237016122aaf5cac97f8e15846cf6">
      <head>Arrangement Note</head>
      <p>The David W. Sharpe Collection is arranged by type of material. Within the correspondence
        folders, materials are arranged in chronological order.</p>
    </arrangement>
    <bioghist id="aspace_789c644d430dd436e3eddb9ec046d93c">
      <head>Biographical Note</head>
      <p>David W. Sharpe enlisted in the Union Army on May 22, 1861. The same day he enlisted in the
        army, he mustered into the 1st Connecticut Heavy Artillery, Co. B. Sharpe mustered out of
        service on September 25, 1865 in Washington, D.C. Following the war, he worked as a laborer
        and supervisor in the bridge industry. He married Emily J. Sharpe. They had a daughter and a
        son. He died on April 13, 1926.</p>
    </bioghist>
